{"title_page": "John Fleck (footballer)", "text_new": "{{short description|Scottish association football player}}\n{{Other people|John Fleck}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = John Fleck\n| image = John Fleck 2019 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Fleck lining up for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] in 2019\n| fullname = John Alexander Fleck<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/-/media/files/thefaportal/governance-docs/registrations/player-registration---july-2016.ashx |title=List of Players under Written Contract Registered Between 01/07/2016 and 31/07/2016 |publisher=The Football Association |page=11 |accessdate=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1991|8|24|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/player/_/id/108374/john-fleck |title=John Fleck |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| height = {{convert|1.70|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/8444/John-Fleck/overview |title=John Fleck: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=13 October 2019}}</ref>\n| position = [[Midfielder]]<ref>{{Hugman|23045|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n| currentclub = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n| clubnumber = 4\n| youthyears1 = 2005\u20132007\n| youthclubs1 = [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]]\n| years1 = 2007\u20132012\n| clubs1 = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| caps1 = 41\n| goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 2012\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 7\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2012\u20132016\n| clubs3 = [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]\n| caps3 = 162\n| goals3 = 8 \n| years4 = 2016\u2013\n| clubs4 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n| caps4 = 155\n| goals4 = 13\n| nationalyears1 = 2007\u20132008\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national under-17 football team|Scotland U17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 9\n| nationalgoals1 = 3\n| nationalyears2 = 2008\u20132010\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland U19]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 4\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2009\u20132012\n| nationalteam3 = [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 4\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2019\u2013\n| nationalteam4 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 2\n| nationalgoals4 = 0\n| club-update = 21:01, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 21:01, 22 February 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n'''John Alexander Fleck''' (born 24 August 1991) is a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for English {{English football updater|SheffieU}} club [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].\n\nHe began his career with [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], making his senior debut in 2008 aged 16, being hyped in the media as a future star,<ref name=cut/><ref name=\"Footballs Top 50 Rising Stars\"/><ref name=Rooney/><ref name=int12/> and later spending a period on loan to [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]. In 2012 he transferred to [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], remaining there until 2016 when he joined Sheffield United, helping the club achieve two promotions in three years, moving up from [[EFL League One|League One]] to the Premier League.\n\n==Early life==\nFleck was born in [[Glasgow]] and was brought up in the city's [[Yoker]] district;<ref name=cut>[https://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/sheffield-united/latest-blades-news/sheffield-united-why-john-fleck-delving-his-past-try-and-take-care-future-148073 Sheffield United: Why John Fleck is delving into his past to try and take care of the future], [[Sheffield Star]], 24 January 2019</ref> he was educated at [[Knightswood Secondary School]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_fa_news.cfm?page=1961&newsCategoryID=3&newsID=1682 |title=Victory Shield Squad for Wales |publisher=Scottish Football Association |date=17 October 2005 |accessdate=3 December 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031085351/https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_fa_news.cfm?page=1961&newsCategoryID=3&newsID=1682 |archivedate=31 October 2016}}</ref> His uncle, former [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] international [[Robert Fleck]], played for [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich]] in the 1980s and 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1026918.html |title=Smith relishes Rangers' 'biggest test' |publisher=FIFA |date=13 February 2009 |accessdate=21 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Rangers===\n[[File:John Fleck.JPG|thumb|upright|Fleck with [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in 2007]]\n\nFleck began his career in the Rangers youth teams;<ref name=cut/> he played in their 5\u20130 [[Scottish Youth Cup]] victory over [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] on 26 April 2007.<ref name=\"Youth Cup\">{{cite news |url=http://www.theherald.co.uk/sport/football/display.var.1359203.0.0.php |title=Rangers U19 5\u20130 Celtic U19 |newspaper=The Herald |location=Glasgow |date=26 April 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070501170835/http://www.theherald.co.uk/sport/football/display.var.1359203.0.0.php |archivedate=1 May 2007}}</ref> On 12 July 2007, Fleck was called up to take part in the full squad pre-season tour of Germany,<ref name=\"Trio Miss Germany Trip\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rangers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Headlines/0,,5~1071698,00.html |title=Trio Miss Germany Trip |publisher=Rangers F.C. |date=12 July 2007}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and was handed his debut for the first team against [[SV Lippstadt 08]] on 15 July 2007, becoming the first 15-year-old to play for the first team since [[Derek Ferguson]]<ref name=\"Debut Double For McCulloch\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rangers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Headlines/0,,5~1073400,00.html |title=Debut Double For McCulloch |publisher=Rangers F.C. |date=16 July 2007}}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> in 1982. Fleck impressed and scored in a 3\u20131 friendly victory over [[Sportfreunde Lotte]] in the next friendly game.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nOn 25 August 2007, just a day after his 16th birthday, Fleck was included for the first time in the Rangers first team squad for a competitive match against [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]. He made his competitive debut on 23 January 2008 in the [[Scottish Cup]] game against [[East Stirlingshire F.C.|East Stirlingshire]]<ref name=\"Rangers 6-0 East Stirlingshire\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/7203278.stm |title=Rangers 6\u20130 East Stirlingshire |website=BBC Sport |date=23 January 2008}}</ref> and made his league debut on 22 May in the final league game of the season against [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]. Two days later, Fleck became the youngest ever player to play in a senior British cup final,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/rangers/6999350/Rangers-blow-as-John-Fleck-and-Danny-Wilson-seek-way-out.html |title=Rangers blow as John Fleck and Danny Wilson seek way out |last=Grahame |first=Ewing |date=15 January 2010 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |accessdate=21 August 2011}}</ref> by appearing as a substitute in the [[2008 Scottish Cup Final]] against [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]].<ref name=2008ScottishCupFinal>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/7416622.stm |title=Queen of the South 2\u20133 Rangers: Report |first=Clive |last=Lindsay |website=BBC Sport |date=24 May 2008 |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref> He gained his first start for Rangers against [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] on 17 January 2009, earning the man of the match award for his performance.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/rangers/4285704/John-Fleck-has-the-talent-to-be-a-Rangers-great-says-Steven-Davis.html |title=John Fleck has the talent to be a Rangers great, says Steven Davis |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=18 January 2009 |accessdate=21 August 2011}}</ref> Five days before this, ''[[The Times]]'' had placed Fleck seventh in their Top 50 Rising Stars of football list.<ref name=\"Footballs Top 50 Rising Stars\">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/european_football/article5502827.ece?token=null&offset=84&page=8 |title=Footballs Top 50 Rising Stars |newspaper=The Times |date=12 January 2009 |location=London |first=Tom |last=Dart |accessdate=6 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nFleck scored his first competitive goal in a 2\u20130 league victory over [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] at [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]] on 31 January 2009.<ref>{{ Cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/7858967.stm | title=Rangers 2\u20130 Dundee United | website= BBC Sport | date=31 January 2009}}</ref> The goal was a 78th-minute penalty, awarded after [[Mihael Kova\u010devi\u0107]]'s challenge had brought Fleck to the ground. Fleck's talent, precocious performances, technique, vision and work-rate led him to be heralded as \"Scotland's [[Wayne Rooney]]\".<ref name=Rooney>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/rangers/4425378/Rangers-teenager-John-Fleck-hailed-as-Scotlands-Wayne-Rooney.html |title=Rangers teenager John Fleck hailed as Scotland's Wayne Rooney |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |author1=Roddy Forsyth |date=1 February 2009 |accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported in August 2009 that Fleck had been dropped from the Rangers first-team after a training ground \"bust-up\" with the assistant manager, [[Ally McCoist]].<ref>{{ Cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/8180391.stm | title=Rangers drop Fleck after bust-up| website=BBC Sport| date=2 August 2009}}</ref> On 26 March 2010, Fleck signed a new three-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/8589788.stm |title=Fleck signs new three-year deal |website=BBC Sport |date=26 March 2010}}</ref> That summer, he had a strong pre-season but then suffered a hamstring injury early in the campaign which hampered his progress.<ref>[https://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/13222969.forgotten-boy-in-blue-john-fleck-set-to-be-man-for-all-seasons/ Forgotten boy in blue John Fleck set to be man for all seasons], Evening Times, 7 July 2011</ref>\n\nWith first team chances in short supply at Rangers, Fleck agreed to move to [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] on a season-long loan at the end of the 2011 summer transfer window<ref name=\"blades move\">{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,,11788_7141949,00.html |title=Blades capture Rangers duo |website=Sky Sports |date=1 September 2011}}</ref> but the deal subsequently fell through as the paperwork was not completed before the deadline.<ref name=\"blades move off\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14741993.stm |title=Sheffield Utd drop bid for Kyle Hutton and John Fleck |website=BBC Sport |date=7 September 2011 |accessdate=7 September 2011}}</ref> In January 2012, having appeared to have seized a fresh chance in the team at Rangers a few weeks earlier,<ref name=int12>[https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/rangers/in-full/interview-john-fleck-rangers-forward-1-2043114 Interview: John Fleck, Rangers forward], ''The Scotsman'', 8 January 2012</ref> Fleck signed for [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] on loan, despite renewed interest from Sheffield United.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/european/rangers_midfielder_john_fleck_completes_blackpool_loan_switch_1_2066433 |title=Rangers midfielder John Fleck completes Blackpool loan switch |newspaper=The Scotsman |location=Edinburgh |date=19 January 2012 |accessdate=19 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Sheffield United back in for Rangers midfielder John Fleck\">{{cite news |title=Sheffield United back in for Rangers midfielder John Fleck |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16373693.stm |accessdate=31 December 2011 |website=BBC Sport |date=31 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, Fleck lodged an objection against his [[Administration and liquidation of The Rangers Football Club plc|contract being transferred to the newco]] set up by [[Charles Green (businessman)|Charles Green]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18616251 |title=Rangers: John Fleck eyes exit as Kyle Hutton stays with newco |website=BBC Sport |date=28 June 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=cut/> [[PFA Scotland]] had previously commented that players were entitled to become [[free agent]]s if they objected to the transfer.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18446597 |title=Rangers: Players free not to join 'newco' says law expert |website=BBC Sport |date=14 June 2012 |accessdate=24 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Coventry City===\nOn 4 July 2012, Fleck joined [[EFL League One|League One]] club [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] after he rejected his Rangers contract being transferred to the new company.<ref>{{cite web |title=City complete Fleck capture |publisher=Coventry City F.C. |date=4 July 2012 |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10269~2831746,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120706235610/http://www.ccfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10269~2831746%2C00.html |archivedate=6 July 2012}}</ref> Rangers were reported to have a sell-on agreement, meaning they would be entitled to a percentage of any transfer fee Coventry subsequently received for the player.<ref>{{cite web |title=John Fleck joins Coventry after leaving Rangers |website=BBC Sport |date=4 July 2012 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18703444}}</ref> Fleck scored his first Coventry goal in a 4\u20131 loss away to [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] from the penalty spot on 18 September 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shrewsbury 4\u20131 Coventry |publisher=Coventry City F.C. |date=18 September 2012 |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?matchid=3518008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130905211101/http://www.ccfc.co.uk/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?matchid=3518008 |archivedate=5 September 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> He struggled to nail down a starting spot in the team during his first season at the club, particularly during the reign of [[Mark Robins]], although he went on to make 35 appearances and scored three times.<ref>{{Soccerbase season|47136|2012}}</ref>\n\nThe arrival of [[Steven Pressley]] as Coventry City manager in March 2013 saw Fleck regain a starting spot in the Coventry City line-up, starting every game of the remaining 2012\u201313 season in a deep-lying central midfield role. Fleck remained first-choice for the following season which Coventry City played at [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]]'s [[Sixfields Stadium]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Coventry City to play home matches at Northampton's Sixfields Stadium |website=Sky Sports |date=8 July 2013 |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11710/8813931/coventry-city-to-play-home-matches-at-northamptons-sixfields-stadium}}</ref> and played a key role in the team as they overcame a 10-point deduction to mount an unlikely play-off push for the first half of the season.<ref>{{cite web |title=John Fleck starting to hit the heights at Coventry after escaping weight of expectation at Rangers |newspaper=Daily Record |location=Glasgow |date=9 January 2014 |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/john-fleck-starting-hit-heights-3003530#uImHIvlqSolJkcMl.97}}</ref>\n\nFleck struggled for form as the team's form collapsed in the remaining months of the 2013\u201314 season but started the following campaign well, putting in a strong performance as the team beat [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] 1\u20130 to mark the club's return to Coventry in September 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coventry City 1\u20130 Gillingham |website=BBC Sport |date=5 September 2014 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/28977757}}</ref> Although his form was up-and-down throughout much of a campaign where the ''Sky Blues'' struggled for consistency, Fleck signed an 18-month contract extension in January 2015 to keep him at the club until the summer of 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=John Fleck: Coventry City midfielder signs new contract |website=BBC Sport |date=7 January 2015 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30714478}}</ref> Between the start of the 2012\u201313 season and the end of the 2013\u201314 season, he scored just one goal for Coventry.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nFleck saw another upturn in form at Coventry City in the 2015\u201316 season where under the management of [[Tony Mowbray]] he was encouraged to play a more forward-thinking role in the team, aided by the defensive support of midfield partner [[Romain Vincelot]]. Fleck's importance to the team was described by Mowbray as being 'the oil in our machine' as the ''Sky Blues'' rose to the top of the League One table.<ref>{{cite news |title='John Fleck is the oil in our machine' \u2013 Coventry City boss knows how vital midfielder is |newspaper=Coventry Telegraph |date=20 October 2015 |url=http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/sport/football/football-news/john-fleck-oil-machine-coventry-10295069}}</ref> Fleck was rewarded for his improvement in 2015\u201316 by being awarded the club's player of the year award by both the fans and his teammates at the club's end of season awards.<ref name=covpoy>{{cite web |title='NEWS: John Fleck wins both CCFC's Players' Player and Player of the Season awards for the 2015/16 season' |publisher=Coventry City F.C. |date=4 May 2016 |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/awards-player-of-the-year-john-fleck-3094426.aspx}}</ref>\n\n===Sheffield United===\nFleck signed a three-year contract with Sheffield United in July 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36745563 |title=Sheffield United sign Jack O'Connell and John Fleck |website=BBC Sport |date=8 July 2016 |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club in a 4\u20131 win over [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]] on 13 November 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37887308 |title=Chesterfield 1\u20134 Sheffield United |website=BBC Sport |date=13 November 2016 |accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref> On 8 April 2017, Fleck scored a late winner against Northampton Town at Sixfields Stadium \u2013 the fans reacted by running onto the pitch to celebrate promotion. On 15 April 2017, United were crowned League One champions and promoted to the Championship. On 22 September 2017, Fleck signed a new four-year contract with the club to keep him at [[Bramall Lane]] until summer 2022.<ref>{{cite news |title=John Fleck: Sheffield United midfielder signs new four-year contract |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41361891 |accessdate=23 September 2017 |website=BBC Sport |date=22 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nFleck has won the [[Sheffield United F.C. Player of the Year|Player of the Year award]] twice whilst at Sheffield United, once in the 2016\u201317 season (tied with teammate [[Billy Sharp]]) and again the next year.<ref name=supoy>{{Cite web |title=Fleck scoops double |url=https://www.sufc.co.uk/news/2018/april/poty-awards/ |publisher=Sheffield United F.C. |date=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 April 2019, Fleck saw his second promotion in three seasons with United, this time to the [[Premier League]], the club returning after a 12-year absence.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48026965 |title=Sheffield United promoted to Premier League after Leeds draw |date=28 April 2019 |accessdate=30 April 2019 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February 2020, Fleck signed a new three year deal <ref> https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11683/11940348/john-fleck-signs-new-sheffield-united-contract</ref>\n\n==International career==\nAfter playing for Scotland at [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21 level]], Fleck was called up to the Scottish senior team for the first time in November 2018.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46233523 Alex McLeish: Scotland boss says nine player withdrawals 'nothing sinister'], BBC Sport, 16 November 2018</ref> He did not play in that match, and had to decline an invitation to join the squad in May 2019 as it clashed with his wedding in [[Ayrshire]], arranged two years earlier when he seemed far less likely to be involved with the national team.<ref>[https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/football/sheffield-united/i-couldn-t-postpone-the-wedding-lauren-would-have-killed-me-john-fleck-on-missing-out-on-scotland-debut-1-9796925 I couldn't postpone the wedding, Lauren would have killed me \u2013 John Fleck on missing out on Scotland debut], Yorkshire Post, 30 May 2019</ref>\n\nOn 10 October 2019, Fleck gained his first senior Scotland [[Cap (sports)|cap]] in a 4\u20130 defeat to [[Russia national football team|Russia]] in [[Moscow]].<ref name=\"ScotRussia\">{{cite news |last1=Forsyth |first1=Roddy |title=Sorry Scotland thrashed by Russia to leave Nations League as their only Euro 2020 hope |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/10/10/scotland-thrashed-russia-leave-nations-league-euro-2020-hope/ |accessdate=13 October 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{Updated|match played 7 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|National Cup{{efn|Includes [[Scottish Cup]], [[FA Cup]]}}\n!colspan=2|League Cup{{efn|Includes [[Scottish League Cup]], [[EFL Cup|League/EFL Cup]]}}\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=6|[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n|[[2007\u201308 Rangers F.C. season|2007\u201308]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|47136|2007|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Scottish Premier League]]||1||0||2||0||0||0||0||0||3||0\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 Rangers F.C. season|2008\u201309]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|47136|2008|accessdate=22 February 2020}}<br />{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7528547.stm |title=Rangers 0\u20130 FBK Kaunas |first=Keir |last=Murray |website=BBC Sport |date=30 July 2008 |accessdate=22 February 2020}}<br />{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7541840.stm |title=FBK Kaunas 2\u20131 Rangers (agg 2\u20131): Report |first=Keir |last=Murray |website=BBC Sport |date=5 August 2008 |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n|Scottish Premier League||8||1||1||0||1||0||0||0||10||1\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 Rangers F.C. season|2009\u201310]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|47136|2009|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n|Scottish Premier League||15||1||3||0||2||1||3{{efn|name=UCL|Appearances in [[UEFA Champions League]]}}||0||23||2\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 Rangers F.C. season|2010\u201311]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|47136|2010|accessdate22 February 2020}}</ref>\n|Scottish Premier League||13||0||1||0||1||0||2{{efn|One appearance in UEFA Champions League, one in [[UEFA Europa League]]}}||0||17||0\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Rangers F.C. season|2011\u201312]]<ref name=sb1112>{{soccerbase season|47136|2011|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n|Scottish Premier League||4||0||1||0||0||0||0||0||5||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!41||2||8||0||4||1||5||0||58||3\n|-\n|[[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] (loan)\n|[[2011\u201312 Blackpool F.C. season|2011\u201312]]<ref name=sb1112/>\n|[[EFL Championship|Championship]]||7||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||8||0\n|-\n|rowspan=5|[[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]\n|[[2012\u201313 Coventry City F.C. season|2012\u201313]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|47136|2012|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n|[[EFL League One|League One]]||35||3||2||0||1||0||4{{efn|name=FLT|Appearance(s) in [[Football League Trophy]]}}||0||42||3\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 Coventry City F.C. season|2013\u201314]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|47136|2013|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n|League One||43||1||4||0||1||0||1{{efn|name=FLT}}||0||49||1\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Coventry City F.C. season|2014\u201315]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|47136|2014|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n|League One||44||0||0||0||1||0||3{{efn|name=FLT}}||0||48||0\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Coventry City F.C. season|2015\u201316]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|47136|2015|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n|League One||40||4||1||0||1||0||1{{efn|name=FLT}}||0||43||4\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!162||8||7||0||4||0||9||0||182||8\n|-\n|rowspan=5|[[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Sheffield United F.C. season|2016\u201317]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|47136|2016|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n|League One||44||4||2||0||1||0||2{{efn|Appearances in [[EFL Trophy]]}}||0||49||4\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Sheffield United F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|47136|2017|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n|Championship||41||2||2||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||44||2\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Sheffield United F.C. season|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|47136|2018|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n|Championship||45||2||0||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||46||2\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Sheffield United F.C. season|2019\u201320]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|47136|2019|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Premier League]]||25||5||0||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||26||5\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!155||13||4||0||4||0||2||0||165||13\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total\n!365||23||20||0||12||1||16||0||413||24\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|match played 19 November 2019}}<ref name=NFT>{{NFT player |id=75728 |name=Fleck, John |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by national team and year\n|-\n!National team!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n|2019||2||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total||2||0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Rangers'''\n*[[Scottish Premier League]]: [[2009\u201310 Scottish Premier League|2009\u201310]],<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Glenda |editor1-last=Rollin |editor2-first=Jack |editor2-last=Rollin |title=Sky Sports Football Yearbook 2010\u20132011 |year=2010 |publisher=Headline Publishing Group |location=London |isbn=978-0-7553-6107-6 |pages=667, 738\u2013739}}</ref> [[2010\u201311 Scottish Premier League|2010\u201311]]<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Glenda |editor1-last=Rollin |editor2-first=Jack |editor2-last=Rollin |title=Sky Sports Football Yearbook 2011\u20132012 |year=2011 |publisher=Headline Publishing Group |location=London |isbn=978-0-7553-6231-8 |pages=687, 758\u2013759}}</ref>\n*[[Scottish Cup]]: [[2007\u201308 Scottish Cup|2007\u201308]]<ref name=2008ScottishCupFinal/>\n\n'''Sheffield United'''\n*[[EFL League One]]: [[2016\u201317 EFL League One|2016\u201317]]<ref>{{cite book |editor-first=John |editor-last=Anderson |title=Sky Sports Football Yearbook 2017\u20132018 |year=2017 |publisher=Headline Publishing Group |location=London |isbn=978-1-4722-3397-4 |pages=326\u2013327}}</ref>\n*[[EFL Championship]] runner-up: [[2018\u201319 EFL Championship|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite book |editor-first=John |editor-last=Anderson |title=Football Yearbook 2019\u20132020 |year=2019 |publisher=Headline Publishing Group |location=London |isbn=978-1-4722-6111-3 |pages=320\u2013231}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[PFA Team of the Year]]: [[PFA Team of the Year (2010s)#League One 8|2016\u201317 League One]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39648483 |title=PFA teams of the year: Chelsea and Tottenham dominate Premier League XI |website=BBC Sport |date=20 April 2017 |accessdate=7 May 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] Player of the Year: [[2015\u201316 Coventry City F.C. season|2015\u201316]]<ref name=covpoy/>\n*[[Sheffield United F.C. Player of the Year|Sheffield United Player of the Year]]: [[2016\u201317 Sheffield United F.C. season|2016\u201317]], [[2017\u201318 Sheffield United F.C. season|2017\u201318]]<ref name=supoy/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{SFA profile}}\n*{{UEFA player}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{2016\u201317 EFL League One PFA Team of the Year}}\n{{Coventry City F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{Sheffield United F.C. Player of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Sheffield United F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fleck, John}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Blackpool F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Coventry City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:People educated at Knightswood Secondary School]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Scottish association football player}}\n{{Other people|John Fleck}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = John Fleck\n| image = John Fleck 2019 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Fleck lining up for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] in 2019\n| fullname = John Alexander Fleck<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/-/media/files/thefaportal/governance-docs/registrations/player-registration---july-2016.ashx |title=List of Players under Written Contract Registered Between 01/07/2016 and 31/07/2016 |publisher=The Football Association |page=11 |accessdate=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1991|8|24|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/player/_/id/108374/john-fleck |title=John Fleck |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| height = {{convert|1.70|m|order=flip}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/8444/John-Fleck/overview |title=John Fleck: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=13 October 2019}}</ref>\n| position = [[Midfielder]]<ref>{{Hugman|23045|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n| currentclub = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n| clubnumber = 4\n| youthyears1 = 2005\u20132007\n| youthclubs1 = [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]]\n| years1 = 2007\u20132012\n| clubs1 = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n| caps1 = 41\n| goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 2012\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 7\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2012\u20132016\n| clubs3 = [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]\n| caps3 = 162\n| goals3 = 8 \n| years4 = 2016\u2013\n| clubs4 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n| caps4 = 155\n| goals4 = 13\n| nationalyears1 = 2007\u20132008\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national under-17 football team|Scotland U17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 9\n| nationalgoals1 = 3\n| nationalyears2 = 2008\u20132010\n| nationalteam2 = [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland U19]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 4\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2009\u20132012\n| nationalteam3 = [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 4\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2019\u2013\n| nationalteam4 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 2\n| nationalgoals4 = 0\n| club-update = 21:01, 7 March 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 21:01, 22 February 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n'''John Alexander Fleck''' (born 24 August 1991) is a Scottish professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for English {{English football updater|SheffieU}} club [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].\n\nHe began his career with [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], making his senior debut in 2008 aged 16, being hyped in the media as a future star,<ref name=cut/><ref name=\"Footballs Top 50 Rising Stars\"/><ref name=Rooney/><ref name=int12/> and later spending a period on loan to [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]. In 2012 he transferred to [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]], remaining there until 2016 when he joined Sheffield United, helping the club achieve two promotions in three years, moving up from [[EFL League One|League One]] to the Premier League.\n\n==Early life==\nFleck was born in [[Glasgow]] and was brought up in the city's [[Yoker]] district;<ref name=cut>[https://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/sheffield-united/latest-blades-news/sheffield-united-why-john-fleck-delving-his-past-try-and-take-care-future-148073 Sheffield United: Why John Fleck is delving into his past to try and take care of the future], [[Sheffield Star]], 24 January 2019</ref> he was educated at [[Knightswood Secondary School]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_fa_news.cfm?page=1961&newsCategoryID=3&newsID=1682 |title=Victory Shield Squad for Wales |publisher=Scottish Football Association |date=17 October 2005 |accessdate=3 December 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031085351/https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_fa_news.cfm?page=1961&newsCategoryID=3&newsID=1682 |archivedate=31 October 2016}}</ref> His uncle, former [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] international [[Robert Fleck]], played for [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich]] in the 1980s and 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1026918.html |title=Smith relishes Rangers' 'biggest test' |publisher=FIFA |date=13 February 2009 |accessdate=21 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Rangers===\n[[File:John Fleck.JPG|thumb|upright|Fleck with [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] in 2007]]\n\nFleck began his career in the Rangers youth teams;<ref name=cut/> he played in their 5\u20130 [[Scottish Youth Cup]] victory over [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] on 26 April 2007.<ref name=\"Youth Cup\">{{cite news |url=http://www.theherald.co.uk/sport/football/display.var.1359203.0.0.php |title=Rangers U19 5\u20130 Celtic U19 |newspaper=The Herald |location=Glasgow |date=26 April 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070501170835/http://www.theherald.co.uk/sport/football/display.var.1359203.0.0.php |archivedate=1 May 2007}}</ref> On 12 July 2007, Fleck was called up to take part in the full squad pre-season tour of Germany,<ref name=\"Trio Miss Germany Trip\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rangers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Headlines/0,,5~1071698,00.html |title=Trio Miss Germany Trip |publisher=Rangers F.C. |date=12 July 2007}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and was handed his debut for the first team against [[SV Lippstadt 08]] on 15 July 2007, becoming the first 15-year-old to play for the first team since [[Derek Ferguson]]<ref name=\"Debut Double For McCulloch\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rangers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Headlines/0,,5~1073400,00.html |title=Debut Double For McCulloch |publisher=Rangers F.C. |date=16 July 2007}}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> in 1982. Fleck impressed and scored in a 3\u20131 friendly victory over [[Sportfreunde Lotte]] in the next friendly game.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nOn 25 August 2007, just a day after his 16th birthday, Fleck was included for the first time in the Rangers first team squad for a competitive match against [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]. He made his competitive debut on 23 January 2008 in the [[Scottish Cup]] game against [[East Stirlingshire F.C.|East Stirlingshire]]<ref name=\"Rangers 6-0 East Stirlingshire\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/7203278.stm |title=Rangers 6\u20130 East Stirlingshire |website=BBC Sport |date=23 January 2008}}</ref> and made his league debut on 22 May in the final league game of the season against [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]. Two days later, Fleck became the youngest ever player to play in a senior British cup final,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/rangers/6999350/Rangers-blow-as-John-Fleck-and-Danny-Wilson-seek-way-out.html |title=Rangers blow as John Fleck and Danny Wilson seek way out |last=Grahame |first=Ewing |date=15 January 2010 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |accessdate=21 August 2011}}</ref> by appearing as a substitute in the [[2008 Scottish Cup Final]] against [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]].<ref name=2008ScottishCupFinal>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/7416622.stm |title=Queen of the South 2\u20133 Rangers: Report |first=Clive |last=Lindsay |website=BBC Sport |date=24 May 2008 |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref> He gained his first start for Rangers against [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] on 17 January 2009, earning the man of the match award for his performance.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/rangers/4285704/John-Fleck-has-the-talent-to-be-a-Rangers-great-says-Steven-Davis.html |title=John Fleck has the talent to be a Rangers great, says Steven Davis |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=18 January 2009 |accessdate=21 August 2011}}</ref> Five days before this, ''[[The Times]]'' had placed Fleck seventh in their Top 50 Rising Stars of football list.<ref name=\"Footballs Top 50 Rising Stars\">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/european_football/article5502827.ece?token=null&offset=84&page=8 |title=Footballs Top 50 Rising Stars |newspaper=The Times |date=12 January 2009 |location=London |first=Tom |last=Dart |accessdate=6 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nFleck scored his first competitive goal in a 2\u20130 league victory over [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] at [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]] on 31 January 2009.<ref>{{ Cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/7858967.stm | title=Rangers 2\u20130 Dundee United | website= BBC Sport | date=31 January 2009}}</ref> The goal was a 78th-minute penalty, awarded after [[Mihael Kova\u010devi\u0107]]'s challenge had brought Fleck to the ground. Fleck's talent, precocious performances, technique, vision and work-rate led him to be heralded as \"Scotland's [[Wayne Rooney]]\".<ref name=Rooney>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/rangers/4425378/Rangers-teenager-John-Fleck-hailed-as-Scotlands-Wayne-Rooney.html |title=Rangers teenager John Fleck hailed as Scotland's Wayne Rooney |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |author1=Roddy Forsyth |date=1 February 2009 |accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported in August 2009 that Fleck had been dropped from the Rangers first-team after a training ground \"bust-up\" with the assistant manager, [[Ally McCoist]].<ref>{{ Cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/8180391.stm | title=Rangers drop Fleck after bust-up| website=BBC Sport| date=2 August 2009}}</ref> On 26 March 2010, Fleck signed a new three-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/8589788.stm |title=Fleck signs new three-year deal |website=BBC Sport |date=26 March 2010}}</ref> That summer, he had a strong pre-season but then suffered a hamstring injury early in the campaign which hampered his progress.<ref>[https://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/13222969.forgotten-boy-in-blue-john-fleck-set-to-be-man-for-all-seasons/ Forgotten boy in blue John Fleck set to be man for all seasons], Evening Times, 7 July 2011</ref>\n\nWith first team chances in short supply at Rangers, Fleck agreed to move to [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] on a season-long loan at the end of the 2011 summer transfer window<ref name=\"blades move\">{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,,11788_7141949,00.html |title=Blades capture Rangers duo |website=Sky Sports |date=1 September 2011}}</ref> but the deal subsequently fell through as the paperwork was not completed before the deadline.<ref name=\"blades move off\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14741993.stm |title=Sheffield Utd drop bid for Kyle Hutton and John Fleck |website=BBC Sport |date=7 September 2011 |accessdate=7 September 2011}}</ref> In January 2012, having appeared to have seized a fresh chance in the team at Rangers a few weeks earlier,<ref name=int12>[https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/rangers/in-full/interview-john-fleck-rangers-forward-1-2043114 Interview: John Fleck, Rangers forward], ''The Scotsman'', 8 January 2012</ref> Fleck signed for [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] on loan, despite renewed interest from Sheffield United.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/european/rangers_midfielder_john_fleck_completes_blackpool_loan_switch_1_2066433 |title=Rangers midfielder John Fleck completes Blackpool loan switch |newspaper=The Scotsman |location=Edinburgh |date=19 January 2012 |accessdate=19 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Sheffield United back in for Rangers midfielder John Fleck\">{{cite news |title=Sheffield United back in for Rangers midfielder John Fleck |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16373693.stm |accessdate=31 December 2011 |website=BBC Sport |date=31 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2012, Fleck lodged an objection against his [[Administration and liquidation of The Rangers Football Club plc|contract being transferred to the newco]] set up by [[Charles Green (businessman)|Charles Green]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18616251 |title=Rangers: John Fleck eyes exit as Kyle Hutton stays with newco |website=BBC Sport |date=28 June 2012 |accessdate=28 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=cut/> [[PFA Scotland]] had previously commented that players were entitled to become [[free agent]]s if they objected to the transfer.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18446597 |title=Rangers: Players free not to join 'newco' says law expert |website=BBC Sport |date=14 June 2012 |accessdate=24 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Coventry City===\nOn 4 July 2012, Fleck joined [[EFL League One|League One]] club [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] after he rejected his Rangers contract being transferred to the new company.<ref>{{cite web |title=City complete Fleck capture |publisher=Coventry City F.C. |date=4 July 2012 |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10269~2831746,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120706235610/http://www.ccfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10269~2831746%2C00.html |archivedate=6 July 2012}}</ref> Rangers were reported to have a sell-on agreement, meaning they would be entitled to a percentage of any transfer fee Coventry subsequently received for the player.<ref>{{cite web |title=John Fleck joins Coventry after leaving Rangers |website=BBC Sport |date=4 July 2012 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18703444}}</ref> Fleck scored his first Coventry goal in a 4\u20131 loss away to [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] from the penalty spot on 18 September 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shrewsbury 4\u20131 Coventry |publisher=Coventry City F.C. |date=18 September 2012 |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?matchid=3518008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130905211101/http://www.ccfc.co.uk/fixtures-results/match-report/index.aspx?matchid=3518008 |archivedate=5 September 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> He struggled to nail down a starting spot in the team during his first season at the club, particularly during the reign of [[Mark Robins]], although he went on to make 35 appearances and scored three times.<ref>{{Soccerbase season|47136|2012}}</ref>\n\nThe arrival of [[Steven Pressley]] as Coventry City manager in March 2013 saw Fleck regain a starting spot in the Coventry City line-up, starting every game of the remaining 2012\u201313 season in a deep-lying central midfield role. Fleck remained first-choice for the following season which Coventry City played at [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]]'s [[Sixfields Stadium]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Coventry City to play home matches at Northampton's Sixfields Stadium |website=Sky Sports |date=8 July 2013 |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11710/8813931/coventry-city-to-play-home-matches-at-northamptons-sixfields-stadium}}</ref> and played a key role in the team as they overcame a 10-point deduction to mount an unlikely play-off push for the first half of the season.<ref>{{cite web |title=John Fleck starting to hit the heights at Coventry after escaping weight of expectation at Rangers |newspaper=Daily Record |location=Glasgow |date=9 January 2014 |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/john-fleck-starting-hit-heights-3003530#uImHIvlqSolJkcMl.97}}</ref>\n\nFleck struggled for form as the team's form collapsed in the remaining months of the 2013\u201314 season but started the following campaign well, putting in a strong performance as the team beat [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] 1\u20130 to mark the club's return to Coventry in September 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coventry City 1\u20130 Gillingham |website=BBC Sport |date=5 September 2014 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/28977757}}</ref> Although his form was up-and-down throughout much of a campaign where the ''Sky Blues'' struggled for consistency, Fleck signed an 18-month contract extension in January 2015 to keep him at the club until the summer of 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=John Fleck: Coventry City midfielder signs new contract |website=BBC Sport |date=7 January 2015 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30714478}}</ref> Between the start of the 2012\u201313 season and the end of the 2013\u201314 season, he scored just one goal for Coventry.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nFleck saw another upturn in form at Coventry City in the 2015\u201316 season where under the management of [[Tony Mowbray]] he was encouraged to play a more forward-thinking role in the team, aided by the defensive support of midfield partner [[Romain Vincelot]]. Fleck's importance to the team was described by Mowbray as being 'the oil in our machine' as the ''Sky Blues'' rose to the top of the League One table.<ref>{{cite news |title='John Fleck is the oil in our machine' \u2013 Coventry City boss knows how vital midfielder is |newspaper=Coventry Telegraph |date=20 October 2015 |url=http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/sport/football/football-news/john-fleck-oil-machine-coventry-10295069}}</ref> Fleck was rewarded for his improvement in 2015\u201316 by being awarded the club's player of the year award by both the fans and his teammates at the club's end of season awards.<ref name=covpoy>{{cite web |title='NEWS: John Fleck wins both CCFC's Players' Player and Player of the Season awards for the 2015/16 season' |publisher=Coventry City F.C. |date=4 May 2016 |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/awards-player-of-the-year-john-fleck-3094426.aspx}}</ref>\n\n===Sheffield United===\nFleck signed a three-year contract with Sheffield United in July 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36745563 |title=Sheffield United sign Jack O'Connell and John Fleck |website=BBC Sport |date=8 July 2016 |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club in a 4\u20131 win over [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield]] on 13 November 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37887308 |title=Chesterfield 1\u20134 Sheffield United |website=BBC Sport |date=13 November 2016 |accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref> On 8 April 2017, Fleck scored a late winner against Northampton Town at Sixfields Stadium \u2013 the fans reacted by running onto the pitch to celebrate promotion. On 15 April 2017, United were crowned League One champions and promoted to the Championship. On 22 September 2017, Fleck signed a new four-year contract with the club to keep him at [[Bramall Lane]] until summer 2022.<ref>{{cite news |title=John Fleck: Sheffield United midfielder signs new four-year contract |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41361891 |accessdate=23 September 2017 |website=BBC Sport |date=22 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nFleck has won the [[Sheffield United F.C. Player of the Year|Player of the Year award]] twice whilst at Sheffield United, once in the 2016\u201317 season (tied with teammate [[Billy Sharp]]) and again the next year.<ref name=supoy>{{Cite web |title=Fleck scoops double |url=https://www.sufc.co.uk/news/2018/april/poty-awards/ |publisher=Sheffield United F.C. |date=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 April 2019, Fleck saw his second promotion in three seasons with United, this time to the [[Premier League]], the club returning after a 12-year absence.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48026965 |title=Sheffield United promoted to Premier League after Leeds draw |date=28 April 2019 |accessdate=30 April 2019 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February 2020, Fleck sign a new three year deal <ref> https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11683/11940348/john-fleck-signs-new-sheffield-united-contract</ref>\n\n==International career==\nAfter playing for Scotland at [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21 level]], Fleck was called up to the Scottish senior team for the first time in November 2018.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46233523 Alex McLeish: Scotland boss says nine player withdrawals 'nothing sinister'], BBC Sport, 16 November 2018</ref> He did not play in that match, and had to decline an invitation to join the squad in May 2019 as it clashed with his wedding in [[Ayrshire]], arranged two years earlier when he seemed far less likely to be involved with the national team.<ref>[https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/sport/football/sheffield-united/i-couldn-t-postpone-the-wedding-lauren-would-have-killed-me-john-fleck-on-missing-out-on-scotland-debut-1-9796925 I couldn't postpone the wedding, Lauren would have killed me \u2013 John Fleck on missing out on Scotland debut], Yorkshire Post, 30 May 2019</ref>\n\nOn 10 October 2019, Fleck gained his first senior Scotland [[Cap (sports)|cap]] in a 4\u20130 defeat to [[Russia national football team|Russia]] in [[Moscow]].<ref name=\"ScotRussia\">{{cite news |last1=Forsyth |first1=Roddy |title=Sorry Scotland thrashed by Russia to leave Nations League as their only Euro 2020 hope |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/10/10/scotland-thrashed-russia-leave-nations-league-euro-2020-hope/ |accessdate=13 October 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{Updated|match played 7 March 2020}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|National Cup{{efn|Includes [[Scottish Cup]], [[FA Cup]]}}\n!colspan=2|League Cup{{efn|Includes [[Scottish League Cup]], [[EFL Cup|League/EFL Cup]]}}\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=6|[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n|[[2007\u201308 Rangers F.C. season|2007\u201308]]<ref>{{soccerbase season|47136|2007|accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Scottish Premier League]]||1||0||2||0||0||0||0||0||3||0\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 Rangers F.C. season